{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596373"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15406"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.19,0.08,0.19,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69793"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55248"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"},{"type":"tags","id":"9507"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69793"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColorectal adenomatous polyps are classified into three histological subtypes: tubular, tubulovillous, and villous. These subtypes have different prevalence rates and risks of malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the prevalence and malignancy risk of colorectal adenomatous polyps?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tubular most common, villous highest risk","Tubular most common, tubulovillous highest risk","Villous most common, tubular highest risk","Tubulovillous most common, villous highest risk","Villous most common, tubulovillous highest risk"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETubular\u003C/strong\u003E adenomas make up about 80% of all colorectal adenomatous polyps and carry the lowest risk of malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVillous\u003C/strong\u003E adenomas are the least common (approximately 5%) but have the highest risk of malignant transformation. \u003Cstrong\u003ETubulovillous\u003C/strong\u003E adenomas show intermediate frequency and risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for malignant transformation include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPolyp size greater than 1 cm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreasing villous architecture\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHigh-grade dysplasia\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular colonoscopy screening allows for early detection and removal of these precancerous lesions, reducing colorectal cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tubular adenomas comprise about 80% of all colorectal adenomatous polyps and have the lowest malignancy risk.","Villous adenomas are rare (5%) but have the highest risk of malignant transformation.","The risk of colorectal cancer increases with polyp size, villous architecture, and grade of dysplasia."],"references":["Hossain MS, Karuniawati H, Jairoun AA, Urbi Z, Ooi J, John A, Lim YC, Kibria KMK, Mohiuddin AKM, Ming LC, Goh KW, Hadi MA. Colorectal Cancer: A Review of Carcinogenesis, Global Epidemiology, Current Challenges, Risk Factors, Preventive and Treatment Strategies. Cancers (Basel). 2022 Mar 29;14(7):1732. doi: 10.3390/cancers14071732. PMID: 35406504; PMCID: PMC8996939.","Duan B, Zhao Y, Bai J, et al. Colorectal Cancer: An Overview. In: Morgado-Diaz JA, editor. Gastrointestinal Cancers [Internet]. Brisbane (AU): Exon Publications; 2022 Sep 30. Chapter 1. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK586003/ doi: 10.36255/exon-publications-gastrointestinal-cancers-colorectal-cancer","Lewandowska A, Rudzki G, Lewandowski T, Stryjkowska-G\u00f3ra A, Rudzki S. Risk Factors for the Diagnosis of Colorectal Cancer. Cancer Control. 2022 Jan-Dec;29:10732748211056692. doi: 10.1177/10732748211056692. PMID: 35000418; PMCID: PMC8753079.","Sawicki T, Ruszkowska M, Danielewicz A, Nied\u017awiedzka E, Ar\u0142ukowicz T, Przyby\u0142owicz KE. A Review of Colorectal Cancer in Terms of Epidemiology, Risk Factors, Development, Symptoms and Diagnosis. Cancers (Basel). 2021 Apr 22;13(9):2025. doi: 10.3390/cancers13092025. PMID: 33922197; PMCID: PMC8122718.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55248"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55248"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:44:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:45:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8097"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69793"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite